  "local_port": 59826,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How much money in charitable donations can a person deduct from his/her taxes before being taxed on his/her donations in the US?",
  "response": "In the United States, the amount you can deduct for charitable donations on your federal income taxes depends on several factors, including the type of donation and the organization you\u2019re donating to. Here's a general overview based on the IRS guidelines as of 2023:\n\n### **1. Percentage Limits Based on Adjusted Gross Income (AGI)**\n\n- **Cash Donations to Public Charities:**\n  - **Maximum Deduction:** Up to **60% of your AGI**.\n  - **Examples of Public Charities:** Churches, educational institutions, hospitals, and other organizations eligible under IRS rules.\n\n- **Donations of Appreciated Assets (e.g., stocks, real estate) to Public Charities:**\n  - **Maximum Deduction:** Up to **30% of your AGI**.\n  - **Benefit:** You may avoid paying capital gains tax on the appreciation of the asset.\n\n- **Donations to Private Foundations, Veterans Organizations, and Certain Other Organizations:**\n  - **Maximum Deduction:** Typically up to **30% of your AGI** for most non-cash donations and **20%** for certain other types.\n\n### **2. Special Rules for 2023**\n\n- **Temporary Adjustments:** Occasionally, the IRS may adjust these limits temporarily (e.g., during the COVID-19 pandemic, there were enhancements to these limits). It's important to consult the latest IRS publications or a tax professional to check if any special provisions are in effect for the current tax year.\n\n### **3. Carryforward of Excess Contributions**\n\n- **If Your Donations Exceed the AGI Limits:**\n  - **Carryforward Period:** You can carry forward excess donations for up to **five subsequent tax years**.\n  - **Usage:** In future years, you can deduct the excess within the same AGI limits applicable to the year of the donation.\n\n### **4. Itemizing Deductions**\n\n- **Standard Deduction vs. Itemizing:**\n  - To benefit from charitable deductions, you must **itemize your deductions** on Schedule A of your tax return.\n  - **Important Note:** If your total itemized deductions, including charitable contributions, do not exceed the IRS standard deduction for your filing status, it may be more beneficial to take the standard deduction instead.\n\n### **5. Documentation and Compliance**\n\n- **Record Keeping:** Maintain proper documentation for all charitable contributions, such as receipts, bank records, or written acknowledgments from the charity.\n- **Qualified Organizations:** Ensure that your donations are made to IRS-qualified charitable organizations to be eligible for deductions.\n\n### **Example Scenario**\n\nSuppose your **Adjusted Gross Income (AGI)** is **$100,000**:\n\n- **Cash Donations to a Public Charity:** You can deduct up to **$60,000**.\n- **Donations of Appreciated Assets to a Public Charity:** You can deduct up to **$30,000**.\n- **Donations to a Private Foundation:** You can deduct up to **$30,000** for most non-cash donations or **$20,000** for certain others.\n\n### **Conclusion**\n\nTo maximize your tax benefits from charitable donations:\n\n1. **Understand the Limits:** Familiarize yourself with the AGI percentage limits based on the type of donation and recipient organization.\n2. **Plan Your Donations:** Consider the timing and type of donations to optimize deductions within the AGI limits.\n3. **Consult a Tax Professional:** Especially if you have significant charitable contributions or complex donation types, seeking professional advice can ensure compliance and optimization of tax benefits.\n\n**Always refer to the latest IRS guidelines or consult with a tax professional**, as tax laws and limits can change.",
